frame.name: Buildings
frame.definition:
<def-root>This frame contains words which name permanent fixed structures forming an enclosure and providing protection from the elements.
<ex>The <fex name="Type">baroque</fex> <t>church</t>, built in 1635, has a very rich interior</ex> <ex>The city tour includes the <fex name="toc">16th-century</fex> <t>monastery</t> of the Transfiguration and Church of Elijah the Prophet</ex> <ex>An ancient <fex name="Mat">stone</fex> <t>church</t> stands amid the fields</ex>
<ex>Jack <gov>built</gov> <x>his <t>house</t></x> in the style of the day.</ex></def-root>

FE.name: Building
FE.definition: <def-root>The entity built by the <fen>Builder</fen> which has some <fen>Function</fen>.</def-root>

FE.name: Function
FE.definition: <def-root>The use for which the <fen>Building</fen> is intended.</def-root>

FE.name: Material
FE.definition: <def-root>Any indication of what makes up the <fen>Building</fen>, including components, ingredients, etc</def-root>

FE.name: Time_of_creation
FE.definition: <def-root>The time at which the <fen>Building</fen> comes into existence.</def-root>

FE.name: Type
FE.definition: <def-root>An indication of the subtype of <fen>Building</fen>, including architectural style.</def-root>

FE.name: Descriptor
FE.definition: <def-root>A characterization of some property of the Building.</def-root>

FE.name: Relative_location
FE.definition: <def-root>A place that a <fen>Building</fen> is located with respect to.</def-root>

FE.name: Possessor
FE.definition: <def-root>The person or other legal entity that owns or has possession of the <fen>Building</fen>.</def-root>

lexUnit.name: house.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building for human habitation

lexUnit.name: houseboat.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a boat which is fitted for use as a dwelling.

lexUnit.name: church.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building used for public Christian worship.

lexUnit.name: tower.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a tall, narrow building, either free-standing or forming part of a building such as a church or castle.

lexUnit.name: bungalow.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a house with only one main storey.

lexUnit.name: cabin.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a small wooden shelter or house.

lexUnit.name: castle.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large building, typically of the medieval period, which is (or was formerly) fortified as a stronghold.

lexUnit.name: condominium.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building or complex containing a number of individually owned flats or houses.

lexUnit.name: cottage.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a small simple house, typically one in the country.

lexUnit.name: dacha.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a country house or cottage in Russia, typically used as a second or holiday home.

lexUnit.name: dormitory.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a bedroom for a number of people in a school or institution.

lexUnit.name: dwelling.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a house or other place of residence.

lexUnit.name: farmhouse.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a house attached to a farm, especially the main house in which the farmer lives.

lexUnit.name: home.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a house or flat.

lexUnit.name: hospital.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a building which houses an institution providing medical, surgical, and nursing care for sick or injured patients.

lexUnit.name: hostel.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: an establishment which provides cheap food and lodging for a specific group of people.

lexUnit.name: hotel.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: an establishment providing accommodation and meals for travellers and tourists.

lexUnit.name: igloo.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a dome-shaped Eskimo house, typically built from blocks of solid snow.

lexUnit.name: lodge.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a small house at the gates of a park or in the grounds of a large house, occupied by a gatekeeper or other employee, or a small country house occupied in season for sports such as hunting and shooting, or a large house or hotel, or a porter's quarters at the main entrance of a college or other large building.

lexUnit.name: mansion.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large, impressive house.

lexUnit.name: monastery.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a building housing a order of monks.

lexUnit.name: motel.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a roadside hotel designed primarily for motorists, typically having the rooms arranged in low blocks with parking directly outside.

lexUnit.name: palace.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large, impressive building forming the official residence of a sovereign, president, archbishop, etc.

lexUnit.name: pension.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a small hotel or boarding house in France and other European countries.

lexUnit.name: pueblo.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: buildings in a town or village in Spain, Latin America, or the south-western US, especially an American Indian settlement

lexUnit.name: residence.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a building which serves as a person's home.

lexUnit.name: shack.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a roughly built hut or cabin.

lexUnit.name: shanty.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a small, crudely built shack.

lexUnit.name: shelter.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a structure giving protection from danger or the elements.

lexUnit.name: tenement.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a separate residence within a house or block of flats.

lexUnit.name: tent.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a portable shelter made of cloth, supported by one or more poles and stretched tight by cords attached to pegs driven into the ground.

lexUnit.name: villa.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a detached or semi-detached house in a residential district, or a large country house, having an estate and consisting of buildings arranged around a courtyard.

lexUnit.name: acropolis.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a citadel or fortified part of an ancient Greek city, built on high ground.

lexUnit.name: arena.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a level area surrounded by seating, in which public events and entertainments are held.

lexUnit.name: auditorium.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large hall used for public gatherings.

lexUnit.name: barn.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large farm building used for storage or for housing livestock.

lexUnit.name: barracks.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large building or group of buildings used to house soldiers.

lexUnit.name: basilica.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large oblong hall or building with double colonnades and a semicircular apse, used in ancient Rome as a law court or for public assemblies, or a similar building used as a Christian church.

lexUnit.name: blockhouse.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a reinforced concrete shelter used as an observation point.

lexUnit.name: campanile.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a bell tower, especially a free-standing one.

lexUnit.name: caravan.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a vehicle equipped for living in, usually designed to be towed.

lexUnit.name: caravanserai.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: inn with a central courtyard for travellers in the desert regions of Asia or North Africa

lexUnit.name: chalet.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a wooden house with overhanging eaves, typically found in the Swiss Alps, or a small wooden cabin used by holidaymakers, typically one in a holiday camp.

lexUnit.name: chateau.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large French country house or castle.

lexUnit.name: conservatory.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a room with a glass roof and walls, attached to a house and used as a sun lounge or for growing delicate plants.

lexUnit.name: garage.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building for housing a motor vehicle or vehicles.

lexUnit.name: gazebo.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a small building, especially one in the garden of a house, that gives a wide view of the surrounding area.

lexUnit.name: greenhouse.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a glass building in which plants that need protection from cold weather are grown .

lexUnit.name: hall.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large room for meetings, concerts, etc., or a university building in which students live, a large country house, or the building of a guild.

lexUnit.name: hangar.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large building with extensive floor area, typically for housing aircraft.

lexUnit.name: hippodrome.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a theatre or concert hall.

lexUnit.name: hovel.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a small squalid or poorly constructed dwelling.

lexUnit.name: inn.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a public house, traditionally an establishment also providing food and lodging.

lexUnit.name: kennel.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a small shelter for a dog.

lexUnit.name: kiosk.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a small open-fronted hut or cubicle from which newspapers, refreshments, tickets, etc. are sold.

lexUnit.name: lighthouse.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a tower or other structure containing a beacon light to warn ships at sea.

lexUnit.name: maisonette.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a set of rooms for living in, typically on two storeys of a larger building and having a separate entrance.

lexUnit.name: mall.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large enclosed shopping area from which traffic is excluded.

lexUnit.name: manor.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large country house with lands.

lexUnit.name: manse.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: the house occupied by a minister of a Scottish Presbyterian Church.

lexUnit.name: mosque.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a Muslim place of worship.

lexUnit.name: outbuilding.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a smaller detached building in the grounds of a main building.

lexUnit.name: outhouse.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a smaller building built on to or in the grounds of a house, or an outside toilet.

lexUnit.name: pagoda.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a Hindu or Buddhist temple or sacred building, typically having a many-tiered tower.

lexUnit.name: palazzo.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a palatial building, especially in Italy.

lexUnit.name: pavilion.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building at a cricket ground or other sports ground used for changing and taking refreshments, a summer house or other decorative shelter in a park or large garden, or a detached or semi-detached block at a hospital or other building complex.

lexUnit.name: penthouse.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a flat on the top floor of a tall building, typically luxuriously fitted and offering fine views.

lexUnit.name: pyramid.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a monumental stone structure with a square or triangular base and sloping sides that meet in a point at the top, especially one built as a royal tomb in ancient Egypt.

lexUnit.name: rotunda.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a round building or room, especially one with a dome.

lexUnit.name: shebang.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a rough hut or shelter.

lexUnit.name: shed.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a simple roofed structure, typically of wood and used for storage or to shelter animals, or a larger structure, typically with one or more sides open, for storing vehicles or machinery, or an open-sided building for shearing sheep or milking cattle.

lexUnit.name: skyscraper.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a very tall building of many storeys.

lexUnit.name: stable.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building for housing horses.

lexUnit.name: stadium.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: an athletic or sports ground with tiers of seats for spectators.

lexUnit.name: supermarket.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large self-service shop selling foods and household goods.

lexUnit.name: synagogue.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building where a Jewish assembly or congregation meets for religious observance and instruction.

lexUnit.name: tabernacle.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a fixed or movable habitation, typically of light construction.

lexUnit.name: tavern.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: an inn or public house.

lexUnit.name: tepee.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a conical tent made of skins or cloth on a frame of poles, used by American Indians of the Plains and Great Lakes regions.

lexUnit.name: terminal.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a departure and arrival building for passengers at an airport.

lexUnit.name: triplex.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building divided into three self-contained residences.

lexUnit.name: warehouse.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large building where raw materials or manufactured goods may be stored.

lexUnit.name: wigwam.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a dome-shaped or conical dwelling made by fastening mats, skins, or bark over a framework of poles.

lexUnit.name: hacienda.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large estate with a house.

lexUnit.name: homestead.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a house, especially a farmhouse, and outbuildings.

lexUnit.name: bunker.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a large container or compartment for storing fuel, or a reinforced underground shelter for use in wartime.

lexUnit.name: theater.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building in which plays and other dramatic performances are given.

lexUnit.name: bar.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: an establishment where alcohol and other refreshments are served.

lexUnit.name: city hall.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: the building or buildings where the administrative offices of a municipal government are located.

lexUnit.name: disco.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a dance club at which music, generally of the style named "disco", is played.

lexUnit.name: discotheque.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a nightclub featuring dancing to live or recorded music.

lexUnit.name: library.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a building or room containing a collection of books and periodicals for use by the public or the members of an institution.

lexUnit.name: temple.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a building devoted to religious worship.

lexUnit.name: building.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a structure with a roof and walls

lexUnit.name: structure.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a building

lexUnit.name: housing.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: houses and flats considered collectively

lexUnit.name: fortress.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a military stronghold, especially a strongly fortified town fit for a large garrison.

lexUnit.name: fortification.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: building or structure for strengthening, securing, and fortifying a location.

lexUnit.name: citadel.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a fortress protecting or dominating a city.

lexUnit.name: fort.n
lexUnit.definition: COD: a fortified building

lexUnit.name: airport.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: the building that houses terminals; the place to go for airplane travel

lexUnit.name: pub.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a place that serves drinks and usually food

lexUnit.name: high-rise.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: a tall, many-storied building.

lexUnit.name: quarters.n
lexUnit.definition: FN: lodgings, especially for members of the military or their families.
